        "url": [
          "https://irreverent.style/posts/stop-and-simply-be/"
        ],
        "name": [
          "Stop and simply be"
        ],
        "published": [
          "2021-06-30"
        ],
        "category": [
          "quote",
          "presented without comment"
        ],
        "content": [
          {
            "html": "<figure class=\"c-blockquote\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>When was young, I had to choose between the life of being and the life of doing. And I leapt at the latter like a trout to a fly. But each deed you do, each act, binds you to itself and to its consequences, and makes you act again and yet again. Then very seldom do you come upon a space, a time like this, between act and act, when you may stop and simply be. Or wonder who, after all, you are.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<figcaption class=\"c-blockquote__attribution\">— Ursula K. Le Guin, The Farthest Shore</figcaption>\n</figure>",
            "value": "When was young, I had to choose between the life of being and the life of doing. And I leapt at the latter like a trout to a fly. But each deed you do, each act, binds you to itself and to its consequences, and makes you act again and yet again. Then very seldom do you come upon a space, a time like this, between act and act, when you may stop and simply be. Or wonder who, after all, you are.\n\n— Ursula K. Le Guin, The Farthest Shore"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": [
        "h-entry"
      ],
      "properties": {
        "url": [
          "https://irreverent.style/posts/newsletters-and-the-seo-game/"
        ],
        "name": [
          "Writing for humans, by humans"
        ],
        "published": [
          "2021-05-13"
        ],
        "category": [
          "email",
          "newsletters",
          "publishing",
          "technology"
        ],
        "content": [
          {
            "html": "<figure class=\"c-blockquote\">\n<blockquote cite=\"https://notesfromasmallpress.substack.com/p/amazon-is-changing-how-we-write\">\n<p>In truth, one reason I enjoy writing these newsletter so much is because they land in your email inbox, sorted by date and time, with my name as the sender. This takes enormous pressure off writing a damned title that is SEO friendly and clicky…Sure, writers must hustle relentlessly to promote their newsletter to potential subscribers, but they do not have to play the exhausting game of ‘can I make you click’ for each post…</p>\n</blockquote>\n<figcaption class=\"c-blockquote__attribution\">— Anne Trubeck, <a href=\"https://notesfromasmallpress.substack.com/p/amazon-is-changing-how-we-write\">Notes from a Small Press - Amazon Is Changing How We Write</a></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>A ‘captive’ audience of willing—paying, even!—subscribers means there is less pressure to play the SEO game. This doesn’t mean titles, subject lines, and headings don’t have to be well written, just that they don’t have to be keyword-stuffed—written for humans, <em>not</em> The Algorithm.</p>",
            "value": "In truth, one reason I enjoy writing these newsletter so much is because they land in your email inbox, sorted by date and time, with my name as the sender. This takes enormous pressure off writing a damned title that is SEO friendly and clicky…Sure, writers must hustle relentlessly to promote their newsletter to potential subscribers, but they do not have to play the exhausting game of ‘can I make you click’ for each post…\n\n— Anne Trubeck, Notes from a Small Press - Amazon Is Changing How We Write\n\nA ‘captive’ audience of willing—paying, even!—subscribers means there is less pressure to play the SEO game. This doesn’t mean titles, subject lines, and headings don’t have to be well written, just that they don’t have to be keyword-stuffed—written for humans, not The Algorithm."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": [
        "h-entry"
      ],
      "properties": {
        "url": [
          "https://irreverent.style/posts/plausible-impossibilities/"
        ],
        "name": [
          "Plausible impossibilities"
        ],
        "published": [
          "2021-05-11"
        ],
        "category": [
          "writing"
        ],
        "content": [
          {
            "html": "<figure class=\"c-blockquote\">\n<blockquote cite=\"https://www.ursulakleguin.com/blog/2015-archive\">\n<p>Literary fantasy is the result of a vivid, powerful, coherent imagination drawing plausible impossibilities together into a vivid, powerful and coherent story…</p>\n</blockquote>\n<figcaption class=\"c-blockquote__attribution\">— Ursula K. Le Guin, <a href=\"https://www.ursulakleguin.com/blog/2015-archive\">“Are they going to say this is fantasy?”</a></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>“plausible impossibilities”…what a wonderfully chewy turn of phrase to describe fantasy.</p>",
            "value": "Literary fantasy is the result of a vivid, powerful, coherent imagination drawing plausible impossibilities together into a vivid, powerful and coherent story…\n\n— Ursula K. Le Guin, “Are they going to say this is fantasy?”\n\n“plausible impossibilities”…what a wonderfully chewy turn of phrase to describe fantasy."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": [
        "h-entry"
      ],
      "properties": {
        "url": [
          "https://irreverent.style/posts/hegemonic-technology/"
        ],
        "name": [
          "Hegemonic technology"
        ],
        "published": [
          "2021-02-15"
        ],
        "category": [
          "technology",
          "typography",
          "publishing"
        ],
        "content": [
          {
            "html": "<figure class=\"c-blockquote\">\n<blockquote cite=\"https://restofworld.org/2021/bringing-urdu-into-the-digital-age/\">\n<p>…technological advances don’t automatically bode well for the digitization of non-Latin type languages.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<figcaption class=\"c-blockquote__attribution\">— Alizeh Kohari, <a href=\"https://restofworld.org/2021/bringing-urdu-into-the-digital-age/\">How to bring a language to the future</a></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>A fascinating (and at times troubling) read about the intersection of calligraphy, typography, the digital era, hegemonic technology, bias in machine learning algorithms, the importance of open source, and a re-visiting of the tension between form and function.</p>\n<p>Also, broaden your own worldview a little and subscribe to <a href=\"https://restofworld.org/\">RestOfWorld</a></p>",
            "value": "…technological advances don’t automatically bode well for the digitization of non-Latin type languages.\n\n— Alizeh Kohari, How to bring a language to the future\n\nA fascinating (and at times troubling) read about the intersection of calligraphy, typography, the digital era, hegemonic technology, bias in machine learning algorithms, the importance of open source, and a re-visiting of the tension between form and function.\nAlso, broaden your own worldview a little and subscribe to RestOfWorld"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
